get data at API¶

In [4]:
def parse():
    try:
        STD_DAY = item.find("stdDay").get_text()
        GUBUN = item.find("gubun").get_text()
        INC_DEC = item.find("incDec").get_text()
        DEF_CNT = item.find("defCnt").get_text()
        DEATH_CNT = item.find("deathCnt").get_text()
        ISOL_CLEAR_CNT = item.find("isolClearCnt").get_text()
        OVER_FLOW_CNT = item.find("overFlowCnt").get_text()
        LOCAL_OCC_CNT = item.find("localOccCnt").get_text()
        QUR_RATE = item.find("qurRate").get_text()
        return {
            "" : STD_DAY,
            "" : GUBUN,
            "  " : INC_DEC,
            " " : DEF_CNT,
            " " : DEATH_CNT,
            "  " : ISOL_CLEAR_CNT,
            " " : OVER_FLOW_CNT,
            " " : LOCAL_OCC_CNT,
            "10 " : QUR_RATE
        }
    except AttributeError as e:
        return {
            "" : np.NaN,
            "" : np.NaN,
            "  " : np.NaN,
            " " : np.NaN,
            " " : np.NaN,
            "  " : np.NaN,
            " " : np.NaN,
            " " : np.NaN,
            "10 " : np.NaN
        }
In [5]:
row = []
for item in items:
    row.append(parse())

In [6]:
df = pd.DataFrame(row)
for i in df.index:
     df.iat[i, 0] = df.iat[i, 0].replace(' ', '-')
for i in df.index:
     df.iat[i, 0] = df.iat[i, 0].replace(' ', '-')
for i in df.index:
     df.iat[i, 0] = df.iat[i, 0].replace(' 00', '')
df = df.iloc[::-1]
df.rename(columns = {'' : ''}, inplace = True)
df = df.set_index([''])
for i in range (1, 10):
    df.drop(('2022-01-27 0' + str(i) + ''), axis = 0, inplace = True)
for i in range (10, 19):
    df.drop(('2022-01-27 ' + str(i) + ''), axis = 0, inplace = True)
df.set_index(pd.to_datetime(df.index))
df.replace('657.29*', '657.29', inplace = True)
df.tail(19)

def print_line_graph(division, df):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(2,2,1)
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(2,2,2)
    ax3 = fig.add_subplot(2,2,3)
    ax4 = fig.add_subplot(2,2,4)
    ax1.plot(df['  '].map(int), color = 'olive', linewidth = 2)
    ax2.plot(df[' '].map(int), color = 'skyblue', linewidth = 2)
    ax3.plot(df[' '].map(int), color = 'magenta', linewidth = 2)
    ax4.plot(df['10 '].map(float), color = 'yellow', linewidth = 2)
    ax1.set_title(division + '   ', size= 15)
    ax2.set_title(division + '   ', size= 15)
    ax3.set_title(division + '   ', size= 15)
    ax4.set_title(division + ' 10 ', size= 15)
    ax1.axes.xaxis.set_ticks([''])
    ax2.axes.xaxis.set_ticks([''])
    ax3.axes.xaxis.set_ticks([''])
    ax4.axes.xaxis.set_ticks([''])
    plt.show()

geo_path = './korea_city_borderline.json'
try:
    geo_data = json.load(open(geo_path, encoding = 'utf-8'))
except:
    geo_data = json.load(open(geo_path, encoding = 'utf-8-sig'))
map_covid = folium.Map(location=[37,127], zoom_start = 7)
folium.Choropleth(geo_data = geo_data,
                  data = df_geo["10 "],
                  columns = [df_geo.index, df_geo["10 "]],
                  key_on='feature.properties.CTP_KOR_NM',
                  fill_color='PuRd',
                  legend_name = '10 ').add_to(map_covid)
display(map_covid)

analyze the correlate between the number of confirmed cases and the number of deaths using machine learning¶

make dataframe to use at machine learning¶

In [29]:
mask = (df[''] == '')
df_machine_learning = df[mask]
df_machine_learning = df_machine_learning[['  ', ' ', ' ', '  ']]

divide into train data and test data¶

In [31]:
X = (pd.DataFrame(range(len(df_machine_learning.index)))).astype('int')
y = df_machine_learning[' '].astype('int')

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 10)

import LinearRegression instance and PolynomialFeatures instance¶

In [32]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures

create a first-order object poly¶

In [34]:
poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=10)
X_train_poly=poly.fit_transform(X_train)

model training with train data¶

In [35]:
pr = LinearRegression()   
pr.fit(X_train_poly, y_train)
Out[35]:
LinearRegression()

calculate the coefficient of determination by applying the test data to the trained model¶

In [36]:
X_test_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_test)
r_square = pr.score(X_test_poly,y_test)
print(r_square)

0.9846929908949009

output a scatter plot of train data and a regression plot predicted by test data as a graph¶

In [37]:
y_hat_test = pr.predict(X_test_poly)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 7))
ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
ax.plot(X_train.to_numpy(), y_train, 'o', label='learned Data', color = 'blue')
ax.plot(X_test.to_numpy(), y_hat_test, 'r+', label='Predicted Value')
ax.legend(loc='best')
plt.xlabel('', size = 20)
plt.ylabel(' ', size = 20)
plt.show()
plt.close()

y_hat = pr.predict(X_ploy)

ax1 = sns.kdeplot(y, label="actual value")
ax2 = sns.kdeplot(y_hat, label="predicted value", ax=ax1)
plt.legend()
plt.show()
